page.text: This document presents the results of the traffic impact analysis prepared for a student-oriented,
cottage-style development, referred to as, “The Retreat”, proposed by Landmark Properties. The
development site is located on the north side of Prices Fork Road opposite the existing
intersections with Brightwood Manor Drive and Huntington Lane in Blacksburg, VA. There are
210 housing units proposed for the development containing 852 bedrooms. Traffic volumes
were projected for Buildout year 2015 assuming a 0.5% annual growth rate.
This study addresses the traffic impacts of the proposed development on the surrounding
transportation network in 2015, the anticipated buildout year of the full development.
Based on direction from the Town of Blacksburg, the study area includes the following
 Prices Fork Road and Hethwood Boulevard
 Prices Fork Road and Sheffield Drive

 Prices Fork Road and Huntington Lane
 Prices Fork Road and Brightwood Manor Drive
 Prices Fork Road and Plantation Road
 Prices Fork Road and University City Boulevard
 Prices Fork Road and West Campus Drive

AM and PM peak hours evaluated.

There are two proposed entrances to the development from Prices Fork Road. Entrance #1 is
opposite of existing Huntington Lane; Entrance #2 is opposite existing Brightwood Manor Drive.
Proposed Entrance #1 is a full access, four-leg intersection. Proposed Entrance #2 is a right-
in/right-out only entrance to the development from westbound Prices Fork Road.
Trips were distributed to each entrance by first considering the characteristic movements of the
site’s anticipated residents: students. The Virginia Tech campus, the primary destination of
students, is located east of the proposed development. Therefore, it is anticipated that
approximately 79% of trips exiting the site will have destinations to the east of the proposed
development. It is anticipated that approximately 20% of trips will have destinations to the west
of the proposed development. Finally, it is anticipated that approximately 1% of trips will have
destinations along Huntington Lane, opposite Entrance #1.
For trips entering the site it is assumed that 79% of trips will be from the east, 20% from the
west, and 1% from the south. For this study, it is anticipated that 65% of the total trips from the
west will enter the site via Entrance #2 and the remaining 14% of the total trips from the west
will enter via Entrance #1. Furthermore, due to the fact that only Entrance #1 contains an
eastbound left, 100% of the trips from the west will enter via Entrance #1. The remaining trips
will enter via Entrance #1 from Huntington Lane.

Synchro traffic software was used to analyze the operational conditions for the study area for the
2013 Existing, 2015 Background and 2015 Buildout conditions. SimTraffic simulation software
was used in conjunction with Synchro to analyze vehicle queues.
Delay within Synchro is reported with a Level of Service (LOS) designation. Level of service is
a quantitative measure of driver perception of delay (waiting time) experienced at an
intersection, and LOS is based on the delay thresholds specified in the Highway Capacity
Manual (HCM). LOS conditions range from “A” (little delay) to “F” (very long delay). Table
7.1 reflects the delay ranges in seconds drivers may experience for a corresponding level of
service for both signalized and unsignalized intersections. The criteria used to measure LOS for
signalized intersections is different from the criteria used for unsignalized intersections. LOS for
signalized intersections is based on control delay per vehicle. Control delay, as defined by
HCM, includes initial deceleration delay, queue move-up time, stopped delay and final
acceleration delay. According to this definition the minimum design acceptable delay is “D” for
design purposes, particularly in a more developed area. For signalized intersections, LOS F
indicates that more than one signal change cycle may be required for a driver to pass through the
intersection. For unsignalized intersections, levels of service are based on critical gap, the
minimum time interval in the major street traffic stream that allows entry for one minor street
vehicle from an intersection, particularly the left turn vehicles. Level of service “E” is generally
considered to be the minimum design standard. At an unsignalized intersection, LOS F occurs
when there are not enough minimum gaps to allow the movements on the minor street to enter
the major street in a "reasonable" amount of time.

have a conflicting movement. In this study, level of service is the basis for the evaluation of
existing and background traffic conditions and the impacts of the traffic generated by the
proposed site on the existing roadway network.

For both the AM and PM peak hours in the 2015 Buildout conditions, the model uses consistent
cycle lengths at the three signalized intersections. In doing so, as seen in Table 7.6 and Table
7.7, the intersection LOS at the intersection of Prices Fork Road and Plantation Road actually
improves from LOS B in the 2015 Background conditions to LOS A in the 2015 Buildout
conditions for the AM peak hour; the LOS remains the same in the PM peak hour at LOS B.
Furthermore, the intersection LOS at the intersection of Prices Fork Road and Heather Drive
improves from the 2015 Background conditions from LOS C to LOS B in the 2015 Buildout
conditions for the AM peak hour; the LOS changes from LOS B in the 2015 Background
conditions to LOS C in the 2015 Buildout conditions. The overall intersection delay changes
from 19.4 seconds to 21.7 seconds in the PM peak hour. The intersection of Prices Fork Road
with University City Boulevard and with West Campus Drive do not change between the 2015
Background conditions and the 2015 Buildout conditions for either the AM or PM peak hours.

Based on the layout of the development and the anticipated traffic distribution, the study
indicates that the Entrance #1/Huntington Lane intersection will meet MUTCD signal
warrants #1 and #2 volume thresholds for justification of a new traffic signal. Traffic
operations at the Entrance #1/Huntington Lane intersection without a signal will result in
LOS F (failure) operations. In the unsignalized scenario it is anticipated that a large
volume of traffic exiting the development will turn right on Prices Fork Road and make a
U-turn at the next intersection at which such turns are legal (Sheffield Drive). This is an
undesirable condition as it will reduce the capacity of the Sheffield Drive intersection.
Due to the proximity of the Entrance #2/Brightwood Manor Drive intersection to the
Plantation Road signalized intersection, a signal was not considered at this intersection.
In Buildout year 2015 the analyses indicate that the proposed development has minimal
impact on operations at the Prices Fork Road intersections with University City
Boulevard and West Campus Drive during the AM and PM peak hours evaluated.
